<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="exploration-4">
  <title>Exploration 4, due February 22</title>
<handout xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="subspace-example">
    <title>Exploration 4, due February 22</title>
  <page>
    <p>
        Make sure to familariaze yourself with the Exploration <xref ref="instructions" text="custom"> Instructions </xref> found on the home page.
      </p>
        
    <p>
      In this exploration, we will walkthrough showing <m>\mathcal{H}=\mathrm{span}\{\vec v_1,\vec v_2\}</m> is a subspace.
    </p>

    <problem xml:id="step1" workspace="1in">
      <title>Create <m>\mathcal{H}</m></title>     
      <statement>
        <p>
          Pick a <xref ref="random" text="custom">random</xref> <m>3 \times 2</m> matrix <m>A</m>. Choose entries not all positive, avoid too many zeros, and do not choose an <m>A</m> that is already in REF.
        </p>
        <p>
          Let <m>\vec v_1=A\vec e_1</m> and <m>\vec v_2=A\vec e_2</m> be the first and second columns of <m>A</m>,
          respectively. Compute <m>\mathrm{rank}(A)</m>. If <m>\mathrm{rank}(A)\neq 2</m>, start over with a new <m>A</m>. Let <m>\mathcal{H} = \textrm{Col}(A) = \textrm{Span}\left\{\vec v_1, \vec v_2\right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    <problem xml:id="step2" workspace="1in">
      <title>Show <m>\mathcal{H}</m> contains zero vector</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that <m>\vec 0 \in \mathcal{H}</m>; that is, show that <m>\vec 0</m> is a linear combination of <m>\vec v_1</m> and <m>\vec v_2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>Step 3 and Question 1</title>
    
    

    <problem xml:id="step3" workspace="3in">
      <title>Show <m>\mathcal{H}</m> is closed under vector addition</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Choose two vectors <m>\vec w_1,\vec w_2\in \mathcal{H}=\mathrm{span}\{\vec v_1,\vec v_2\}</m>
          by selecting <xref ref="random" text="custom">random</xref> scalars <m>c_1,c_2</m> and forming
          <m>c_1\vec v_1+c_2\vec v_2</m>. Do this twice with different weights to obtain <m>\vec w_1</m> and <m>\vec w_2</m>. Let <m>\vec z=\vec w_1+\vec w_2</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Verify</strong> that <m>\vec z \in \mathcal{H}</m> by showing that the matrix equation <m>A\vec x = \vec z</m> has a solution. Check by expressing <m>\vec z</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    <question>
      <title>Fill in the blanks</title>
      <p>
        When you write <m>\vec z</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2</m>, then the weights are the
        <m>\framebox[4in]{ }</m> from the linear combination of writing
        <m>\framebox[2in]{ }</m> as linear combinations of <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2</m>.
      </p>
    </question>
  </page>

  <!-- ================= PAGE 4 ================= -->
  <page>
    <title>Step 4 and Conclusion</title>

    <problem xml:id="step4" workspace="4in">
      <title>Show <m>\mathcal{H}</m> is closed under scalar mutiplication</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\vec w</m> be either <m>\vec w_1</m> or <m>\vec w_2</m> from <xref ref="step3"/>. Choose a <xref ref="random" text="custom">random</xref> scalar <m>c</m> and check that <m>c\vec w</m> is in the column space of <m>A</m> by showing that <m>A\vec x = c\vec w</m> has a solution. Then confirm by expressing <m>c\vec w</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vec v_1</m> and <m>\vec v_2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    <question workspace="0.5in">
      <title>Fill in the blanks</title>
      
      
      <p>
        When you write <m>c\vec w</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2</m>, then the weights are the
        <m>\framebox[4in]{ }</m> from the linear combination of writing
        <m>\framebox[2in]{ }</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2</m>.
      </p>
    </question>


    <problem xml:id="conclusion" workspace="1.5in">
      <title>Conclusion</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Try to convince yourself that for any choice of <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2</m>, the set
          <m>\mathcal{H}=\mathrm{span}\{\vec v_1,\vec v_2\}</m> always contains <m>\vec 0</m> and is always closed under vector addition and scalar multiplication. Provide one or two sentences justifying this fact.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    </page>
</handout>
</section>